## 📊 Part 6 — Results and Observations

### 🔹 Open-Loop Response
![Open Loop](results/open_loop_response.png)

The motor response is slow and takes longer to reach steady-state without any control.

---

### 🔹 PID Response
![PID](results/pid_response.png)

The PID controller significantly improves response speed, reduces rise time, and eliminates steady-state error with minimal overshoot.

---

### 🔹 Gain-Scheduled Response
![Gain Scheduled](results/gainscheduled_response.png)

The gain-scheduled controller adapts to different throttle levels, providing smooth performance at low speeds and faster response at high speeds.

---

### 🔹 Comparison Plot
![Comparison](results/comparison_plot.png)

The comparison shows that:
- Open-loop response is slow  
- PID improves speed and stability  
- Gain scheduling provides the best overall performance across all operating conditions  

---

## ✅ Conclusion

The project demonstrates that PID control significantly enhances system performance compared to open-loop operation. Gain scheduling further improves adaptability across different throttle levels, making the system more suitable for real-world electric vehicle applications.

